sbol:Collection.dcterms:title: iGEM Parts Registry
sbol:Collection.dcterms:description: The iGEM Registry is a growing collection of genetic parts that can be mixed and matched to build synthetic biology devices and systems. As part of the synthetic biology community's efforts to make biology easier to engineer, it provides a source of genetic parts to iGEM teams and academic labs.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: This is a recombination site for cre recombinase. Please note that it is in reverse direction.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Ryo Kariyazono, Ryosuke Kamei
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: It was synthesized in oligonucleotide form.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_B0012
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Transcription terminator for the E.coli RNA polymerase.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Reshma Shetty
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: Derived from the TE terminator of T7 bacteriophage between Genes 1.3 and 1.4 <genbank>V01146</genbank>.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes:
Suggested by Sri Kosuri and Drew Endy as a high efficiency terminator. The 5' end cutoff was placed immediately after the TAA stop codon and the 3' end cutoff was placed just prior to the RBS of Gene 1.4 (before AAGGAG).

Use anywhere transcription should be stopped when the gene of interest is upstream of this terminator.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: tetA(C)b
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: This is the coding region for Tetracyline resistance in the reverse orientation. If a promoter adn RBS are placed downstream and the entire region, from promoter to stop codon is flipped the cell will express tetracycline resistance.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Sabriya Rosemond, Erin Zwack
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: It was cloned into PsB1A2 plasmids.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: lox71
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription:
Lox71 is a site specific recombination cassette. It belongs to the loxP family frequently used in genetics, particularly in mouse genetics.
lox site recombination is catalysed by a Site specific recombinase, Cre.
lox sequences are composed of an 8 bp Core sequence surrounded by two Arms.
The particularity of lox66 is that it has an altered sequence at the end of it's left arm compared to loxP. This sequence variation reduces affinity of the Cre recombinase for the arm. As a consequence, after a recombination between a lox71 and a lox66 (altered right arm sequence), one of the two resulting generated lox sites has very low recombination potential as it inherited both mutated arms. Use of lox71 & lox66 sites is potentially interesting when the recombination reaction must be "irreversible".
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Eimad Shotar
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance:
This part was generated in the form of a forward & a reverse primer. After annealing these primers EcoRI & PstI compatible cohesive ends at the 5' & 3' ends of the dsDNA were generated.
Next, the dsDNA was subcloned in a pSB1A2 open plasmid (digested with EcoRI & PstI)
You can follow the construction process by following the links available in the Paris iGEM 2007 wiki:
http://parts.mit.edu/igem07/index.php/Paris "freezer" section plasmids table. A links sends you to the corresponding notebook date when the ligation reaction was performed
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: No modifaication was made on lox71 sequence

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_I712074
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:description: T7 promoter (strong promoter from T7 bacteriophage)
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: T7 promoter is very specific promoter which is transcribed only by specific T7 RNA polymerase. Usually this promoter is used in expression systems where T7 promoter is cotransfected with T7 RNA polymerase. That ensures strong transcription of desired genes.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Rok Gaber

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_B0011
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Bidirectional transcriptional terminator consisting of a 22 bp stem-loop.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Reshma Shetty
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: Derived from luxICDABEG operon terminator of Vibrio fischeri <genbank>AF170104</genbank>.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: In the naturally-occuring sequence there is a mismatch in the stem of the stem loop. This can be corrected via an A->G mutation (at position 40 -- sequence coordinate/not MFOLD coordinate). The above sequence does not reflect this mutation (but the MFOLD image does). This terminator's location cannot be found using some inverted repeat detectors like PALINDROME because it is too short and contains a mismatch. This one was found with the help of Tom Knight. It lies between two coding regions that point towards eachother.
